ges = 186\u2013187}}</ref> The two artists began a correspondence on the subject and Bigot became extremely interested in Carri\u00e8s' work.{{Sfn|Simier|5=2007|p=74, 90|id=Simier}} Bigot's knowledge of chemistry allowed him to become an adviser to [[Ernest Chaplet]] for his sculpture and Carri\u00e8s as well as a collaborator with the chemist [[Henry Le Chatelier]].<ref name=\":2\" /> On the practical side (turning and modeling), he benefitted from the advice of [[Rapha\u00ebl Tessier]] (1860-1937).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Career in Ceramics==\nIn 1894, Bigot presented his pieces for the first time at the Salon of the Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 nationale des Beaux-Arts. The ceramics used a simple form ornamented with matte enamel using shades of yellow, green, and brown, often with the effect of crystallization. In 1895, he participated in the inaugural exposition of Siegfried Bing's La Maison de l'Art Nouveau, which gave its name to the style.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite book|language=fr|name=Arlette Barr\u00e9-Despond|title=Dictionnaire international des arts appliqu\u00e9s et du design|location=Paris|publisher=[[\u00c9ditions du Regard]]|date=1996|isbn=2-84105-024-6}}</ref>\n\nThe year 1897 marked a turning point. Architectural ceramics were reaching the pinnacle of their popularity and Bigot took the opportunity to found his own company, ''A. Bigot et Cie''. This enterprise, which employed up to 150 workers and counted 10 industrial kilns, produced numerous trinkets, vases and vessels which were on display in his shop, which he transferred in Paris from the rue d'Assas to the rue des Petites-\u00c9curies.\n\nAlong with Emile Muller, Bigot thus became the principal figure in architectural ceramics in France, and from 1898 he worked to integrate ceramics with fa\u00e7ades of reinforced concrete. This architectural outlet explains, by implication, the membership of his company in the Union Syndicale des architetes, but also the relaxation of the urban regulations of 1882 which favored the appearance of projecting elements, such as oriel bays, that broke up the uniformity of fa\u00e7ades.\n\nThe collaboration with [[Hector Guimard]] at the end of the decade marked the beginning of Bigot's fame with architectural ceramics. Before then his work had been confined essentially to baths and restaurants. But in 1898, Guimard's Castel Beranger emerged as the manifesto of Art Nouveau in architecture and its ceramics were commissioned from Bigot, who decorated the fa\u00e7ade with picturesque details and covered the entrance breezeway with highly plastic molded panels designed to evoke the atmosphere of a grotto. The material became thus emblematic of the new style before Art Nouveau's decline about 1910.\n\n==Selected works==\n===Castel B\u00e9ranger, 1894-5===\nArchitect: Hector Guimard\n\n===Paris Exhibition of 1900===\nBigot fabricated Ren\u00e9 Binet\u2019s designs for the main gateway to the Paris Exhibition of 1900.<ref>Madsen 1967, p. 116</ref>  Bigot's work was acquired in its entirety by Jen\u0151 Radisics, the director of the [[Museum of Applied Arts (Budapest)|Budapest Museum of Applied Arts]] and remained in store until 2013, when much of it was displayed at the Museum.\n\n===Avenue Rapp No. 29, 1901===\nThe [[Lavirotte Building]], designed by Jules Lavirotte, Avenue Rapp no. 29, Paris was the residence of Alexandre Bigot.\n<blockquote>\nIn 1901, Jules Lavirotte\u2019s design for this won a municipal competition as the year\u2019s best.  Its extraordinary portal is the ultimate in Art Nouveau exuberance.  The carved elements feature a central bust of a woman with flowing hair, balanced by carved naked figures rising above the sides.<ref>Borrus 2003, p. 254-255</ref>\n</blockquote>\n<gallery>\nImage:No 29 Avenue Rapp.jpg\nImage:No 29 Avenue Rapp entryway.jpg\nImage:Immeuble Lavirotte 2007.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n===Rue d'Abbeville No. 14, 1901===\nArchitects: Alexandre & Edouard Autant\n\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011070821/http://www.paris-architecture.info/PA-053.htm Source]\n\n===Avenue De Wagram No. 34 (Ceramic Hotel), 1904===\n<blockquote>\nThis reinforced concrete building, built by Jules Lavirotte, was nicknamed \"Ceramic Hotel\" for its glazed earthenware fa\u00e7ade, created by Alexandre Bigot and sculpted by [Camille Alaphilippe].  Exemplifying the sensual Art Nouveau style of turn-of-the-century Paris, this residence won the city prize for the best fa\u00e7ade of 1905.<ref>Borrus 2003, p. 294-5</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n===Saint Jean de Montmartre===\nArchitect: Anatole de Baudot\n\n<gallery>\nImage:St Jean de Montmartre.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n===Rue Franklin No. 25, 1904===\nArchitect: Auguste Perret\n\n[http://fr.structurae.de/structures/data/index.cfm?id=s0008987 Info]\n\n===Rue Campagne-Premiere No. 31, 1911===\nArchitect: Andre Arfidson\n\t<blockquote>\nCeramic detailing gives this industrial fa\u00e7ade charm and helped the architect win an award for its frontage in 1911 from the Town of Paris.  The sandstone tiling by ceramist Alexandre Bigot covers this reinforced concrete duplex of twenty workshops with residences.  The three-dimensional floral elements add geometric patterning to the piers and around the window borders.<ref>Borrus 2003, p. 433</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n===Smaller Works===\n<gallery>\nFile:Doorway Alexandre Bigot ceramic tiles.jpg|Ceramic tiles by Alexandre Bigot, rue Mademoiselle, Paris\nFile:Alexandre Bigot ceramic tile detail.jpg|Detail from rue Mademoiselle\nFile:Alexandre Bigot ceramic tile detail - 2.jpg|Detail from rue Mademoiselle\n</gallery>\n\n==United States Patents==\n\nPatent No. 838,496.  Application Filed: February 17, 1903.  Patented: December 11, 1906. [http://www.google.com/patents?id=eU1HAAAAEBAJ&printsec=abstract&zoom=4&dq=alexandre+bigot+patent&source=gbs_summary_r&cad=0_0 Link]\n\n*A process for the manufacturing of glazed or enameled ceramic ware.\n\nPatent No. 1,497,084.  Application Filed: October 6, 1920.  Patented: June 10, 1924. [http://www.freepatentsonline.com/1497084.html Link]\n\n*A drying kiln for the production of ceramic ware.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Borrus,Kathy, ''One Thousand Buildings of Paris'', 2003, Black Dog & Leventhal Publishers, Inc.\n*Madsen, Stephan Tschudi, ''Art Nouveau'', 1967\n*Turner, Jane (editor), ''The Dictionary of Art'', 1996, Macmillan Publishers Limited\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Alexandre Bigot}}\n*[http://www.google.com/patents?id=eU1HAAAAEBAJ&printsec=abstract&zoom=4&dq=alexandre+bigot+patent&source=gbs_summary_r&cad=0_0 United States Patent No. 838,496]\n*[http://www.freepatentsonline.com/1497084.html United States Patent No. 1,497,084]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081120050421/http://www.paris-architecture.info/PA-054.htm 31, rue Campagne Premi\u00e8re]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090810230912/http://www.jasonjacques.com/works/alexandre-bigot/ Bio at Jason Jacques Inc]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081011070821/http://www.paris-architecture.info/PA-053.htm Rue d'Abbeville No. 14 Info]\n*[http://fr.structurae.de/structures/data/index.cfm?id=s0008987 Rue Franklin No. 25 Info]\n*[http://lartnouveau.com/artistes/bigot.htm lartnouveau.com]\n*[http://lartnouveau.com/artistes/bigot.htm Alexandre Bigot] - current photographs\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090227013834/http://lesamisducastellouis.fr/New%20Site/historique.html Le Castel Louis]\n*[http://www.imm.hu/en/exhibits/view/217,The+Bigot+Pavilion+%E2%80%93+Art+Nouveau+Architectural+Ceramics+from+Paris?type=temporary Budapest Museum of Applied Arts]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bigot, Alexandre}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:French ceramists]]\n[[Category:Art Nouveau artists]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer in Ceramics:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandre_Bigot"}
{"title_page": "2007\u201308 Kilmarnock F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club = [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]\n| season =[[2007\u201308 in Scottish football|2007\u201308]]\n| chairman =Michael Johnston \n| manager =[[Jim Jefferies (footballer)|Jim Jefferies]]\n| stadium =[[Rugby Park]]\n| league = [[2007\u201308 Scottish Premier League|Premier League]]\n| league result ='''Eleventh Place'''  \n| cup1 = [[2007\u201308 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]\n| cup1 result ='''Fifth Round''', lost to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] \n| cup2 = [[2007\u201308 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] \n| cup2 result ='''Third Round''', lost to [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]\n| league topscorer =<br />[[Colin Nish|Colin Nish]] (7)\n| season topscorer =<br />[[Colin Nish|Colin Nish]] (9)\n| highest attendance =10,546 v [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], 17 February 2008 <!--LEAGUE ONLY-->\n| lowest attendance  =4,086 v [[Gretna F.C.|Gretna]], 26 April 2008 <!--LEAGUE ONLY-->\n| average attendance =League: 6,181\n|  pattern_la1 = _bluelower\n |  pattern_b1 = _bluestripes\n |  pattern_ra1 = _bluelower\n |  pattern_sh1 = _white border\n |  pattern_so1 = _whitetop\n |  leftarm1 = \n |  body1 = \n |  rightarm1 = \n |  shorts1 = 0033FF\n |  socks1 = 0033FF\n |  pattern_la2 = \n |  pattern_b2 = _Lottoblue\n |  pattern_ra2 = \n |  pattern_sh2 = _lightblue stripes\n |  pattern_so2 = _bluetop\n |  leftarm2 = FFFF00\n |  body2 = FFFF00\n |  rightarm2 = FFFF00\n |  shorts2 = FFFF00\n |  socks2 = FFFF00\n| prevseason = [[2006\u201307 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2006\u201307]]\n| nextseason = [[2008\u201309 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2008\u201309]]\n}}\n\nThe [[2007\u201308 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]] was [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock's]] ninth consecutive season in the [[2007\u201308 Scottish Premier League|Scottish Premier League]], having competed in it since its inauguration in [[1998\u201399 Scottish Premier League|1998\u201399]]. Kilmarnock also competed in the [[2007\u201308 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] and the [[2007\u201308 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]].\n\n\n==Summary==\n\n===Season===\nKilmarnock finished eleventh in the [[2007\u201308 Scottish Premier League|Scottish Premier League]] with 40 points.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/table/_/league/SCO.1/season/2007/scottish-premiership | title=Scottish Premiership Table 2007-08 | publisher=[[ESPN FC]] | work=espnfc.com | accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> They reached the second round of the [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]], losing to [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/matchstats?gameId=228979 | title=Hamilton Academical vs. Kilmarnock | publisher=[[ESPN]] | work=espnfc.com | date=25 September 2007 | accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> and the fifth round of the [[Scottish Cup]], losing to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match?gameId=235921 | title=Kilmarnock vs. Celtic | publisher=[[ESPN]] | work=espnfc.com | date=2 February 2008 | accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==Results and fixtures==\n{{legend2|#ccffcc|Win|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#ffffcc|Draw|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#ffcccc|Loss|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#cccccc|Postponed|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n===Scottish Premier League===\n{{Main article|2007\u201308 Scottish Premier League}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:center\"\n!Match!!Date!!Opponent!!Venue!!Result!!Attendance!!Scorers\n|-style=\"background: #FFFFCC;\"\n|1||5 August 2007||[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]||A||0\u20130||60,000||\n|-style=\"background: #CCFFCC;\"\n|2||13 August 2007||[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]||H||2\u20131||5,557||[[Willie Gibson (footballer, born 1984)|Gibson]] 79\u2019 [[Colin Nish|Nish]] 87\u2019\n|-style=\"background: #CCFFCC;\"\n|3||18 August 2007||[[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]|